03706nam a22005295i 9780520964648DE-B159720200424112023.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200424t20162016cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209646487 a10.1525/97805209646482doi  a(DE-B1597)519731  a(OCoLC)951625708  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aBL2016.H56 7aREL0840002bisacsh04a200.954522231 aElmore, Mark, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aBecoming Religious in a Secular Age /cMark Elmore. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2016] 4c©2016  a1 online resource (304 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tIntroduction: What Is This Thing Called Religion? -- t1. Becoming Sufficiently Developed in Himachal Pradesh, or How Religion Became a Problem -- t2. God Is a Beggar: Land Reforms Create Religion as a Separate Sphere -- t3. Ordinary Miraculousness: Farmers and Pharmacists Practice the Science of Religion -- t4. Managing Religion: Government, Gūrs, and Gods -- t5. Negotiating Religion: Normalization, Abjection, And Enrichment -- t6. Cultivating Religion Amid The Conflicting Desires Of Goats, Gods, And Government -- tAfterword: Religion Is A Verb -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aReligion is often viewed as a universally ancient element of the human inheritance, but in the Western Himalayas the community of Himachal Pradesh discovered its religion only after India became an independent secular state. Based on extensive ethnographic and archival work, Becoming Religious in a Secular Age tells the story of this discovery and how it transformed a community's relations to its past and to its members, as well as to those outside the community. And, as Mark Elmore demonstrates, Himachali religion offers a unique opportunity to reimagine relations between religion and secularity. Elmore shows that modern secularity is not so much the eradication of religion as the very condition for its development. Showing us that to become a modern, ethical subject is to become religious, this book creatively augments our understanding of both religion and modernity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 7aRELIGION / Religion, Politics & State.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook-Package 2016z978311066754708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook-Package 2016-2018z978311063539308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUCal Press eBook Package 2014-2016z978311065748740uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520964648423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780520964648.jpg  a978-3-11-063539-3  UC Press eBook-Package 2016-2018c2016d2018  a978-3-11-065748-7  UCal Press eBook Package 2014-2016c2014d2016  a978-3-11-066754-7  UC Press eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles